\begin_layout Subsection
Time Dilation & the Lorentz Factor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Special Relativity (SR) is fascinating because it suggests that some of
 the seemingly foundational aspects of normal experience (and the physical
 reality which underpins it) aren't quite so in general.
 The forward flow of time, which once seemed an inescapable constant, uniform
 for all observers, turns out to be completely dependent upon the relative
 velocity of entities.
 Frames of reference in relative motion record each other's clocks as advancing
 more slowly, as given by the time dilation factor:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\gamma\equiv dt/d\tau\text{ , the Time Dilation Factor}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $d\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

 are infinitesimal time increments, where 
\begin_inset Formula $d\tau$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 measured between events by a clock at rest in a given frame, and 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the time intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 between the same events given by the first clock, but as measured in another
 coordinate frame.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 gives the ratio of time intervals as measured by a pair of clocks in different
 frames.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none
The time dilation factor is given by the Lorentz term, which is crucial
 in SR:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\gamma(v)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-v^{2}/c^{2}}}\text{ , the Lorentz Factor}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is the speed of one frame relative to another, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the speed of light.
 Because all objects with mass move slower than light, as their speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v<c$
\end_inset

 increases, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{1-v^{2}/c^{2}}<1$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>1$
\end_inset

 goes to positive infinity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none
Thus, we can see how clocks at relativistic speeds are seen to advance at
 a reduced rate, as proper time intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau$
\end_inset

 in the clock's rest frame appear stretched according to the time dilation
 factor:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Delta t=\gamma\Delta\tau\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

