\begin_layout Subsection
Universal Speed of Light and Velocity Addition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The speed of light, a constant according to SR, shatters another foundation
 of our experience - the idea that we can generally approach the velocity
 of objects moving relative to us by accelerating out of our old frame of
 reference.
 This is not true in the case of light, as time dilation conspires to ensure
 that our clocks slow down as we approach the velocity of photons (as seen
 from an external frame) so that they always seem to remain at 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 relative to us.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our inability to catch up with light is a special case of SR's contradiction
 of Galilean velocity addition; in SR, if we are interested in the velocity
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 of an object, then finding the velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{B}$
\end_inset

 as measured in frame B with known velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{A}$
\end_inset

 as measured in frame A is no longer as simple as saying:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
u_{B}=u_{A}-v_{B,A}=u_{A}+v_{A,B}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula \[
\text{ Galilean velocity addition (not generally true)}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Where the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{B}$
\end_inset

 reads 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 as measured in B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{A,B}$
\end_inset

 reads 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the velocity of frame A as measured in B.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) Instead, we now have the following relation for parallel velocities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
u_{B}=\frac{u_{A}+v_{A,B}}{1+u_{A}v_{A,B}/c^{2}}\text{ , velocity addition in SR}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

