\begin_layout Subsection
Length Contraction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as time dilation describes how moving clocks are seen to run slower,
 length contraction in SR tells us that distances measured outside an object's
 rest frame appear contracted along the direction of motion.
 Like the proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, an object's proper length 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{0}$
\end_inset

 measured in its frame of rest is related to the length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 in general frames of motion by the Lorentz factor:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
L=\frac{L_{0}}{\gamma}\]

\end_inset

With the proper length divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>1$
\end_inset

, we see the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{0}$
\end_inset

 will be the longest seen in any frame.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Coordinate Transformations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lorentz equations which map event coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,t)$
\end_inset

 in frame 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(x',t')$
\end_inset

 in frame 
\begin_inset Formula $S'$
\end_inset

 (moving in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 direction at speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

) are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
x' & = & \gamma\,(x-vt)\\
t' & = & \gamma\,(t-vx/c^{2})\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lorentz transformation can be expressed using a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{L}$
\end_inset

 which performs an operation mapping column vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x'}$
\end_inset

 (mixing the space and time components in the process in a rotation-like
 fashion).
 The equation for the transformed space-time component 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x'}$
\end_inset

 takes the general form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x'}=\mathbf{L}\mathbf{x}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Worldlines program, I've used the following explicit matrix form
 for the Lorentz transformation in the case of one-dimensional motion along
 the positive 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 direction:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
x'\\
y'\\
ct'\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\gamma & 0 & -\beta\gamma\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
-\beta\gamma & 0 & \gamma\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
x\\
y\\
ct\end{array}\right]\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\text{Where: }\beta=v/c\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the inverse Lorentz transform, which takes coordinates in the
 moving frame just described and maps them into the world frame, has the
 general form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x=}\mathbf{L^{-1}x'}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where I've used the following explicit matrix form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
x\\
y\\
ct\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\gamma & 0 & \beta\gamma\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\beta\gamma & 0 & \gamma\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
x'\\
y'\\
ct'\end{array}\right]\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is basically the standard configuration for the Lorentz transformation
 (but with the time coordinate listed last), in which the difference between
 the forward and inverse transformations is just a change in sign.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since for a pair of frames with coordinate axes facing the same direction,
 relative velocities for the same action will have opposite sign, whether
 the motion is towards or away.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Use in Worldlines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, when drawing the axes basis and grid of a particle, the inverse
 transform corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{particle}$
\end_inset

 is used to map 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{basis_{rest}}$
\end_inset

, the basis vectors of the particle's coordinate system in its rest frame,
 into the world frame:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
r_{basis_{world}}=L^{-1}\left(r_{basis_{rest}},\, v_{particle}\right)\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, any display transforms for the target particle are applied to the
 world coordinates of the vector:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
r_{basis_{display}}=L\left(r_{basis_{world}},\, v_{target}\right)\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{-1}$
\end_inset

 apply the regular or inverse Lorentz transformation matrix to the vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, given velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In constructing 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 suitable for 2 dimensional velocities 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, first an inverse rotation matrix for the particle's heading is applied;
 this is then multiplied by the 1D Lorentz matrix; last the regular rotation
 matrix is applied:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
L_{2D}(v)=R(\theta_{v})\, L_{1D}(v)\, R^{-1}(\theta_{v})\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\text{Where: }\theta_{v}=tan^{-1}(v_{y}/v_{x})\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

